			<li>
			<h3>Course Content</h3>
			
				<p>The NEBOSH International Fire Certificate course is split into three units of study, each of which is assessed separately:<br /><br />

				Unit IGC I: Management of International Health & Safety<br /><br />

				Foundations in Health &amp; Safety<br />
				Health &amp; Safety management systems – Policy<br />
				Health &amp; Safety management systems – Organising<br />
				Health &amp; Safety management systems – Planning<br />
				Health &amp; Safety management systems – Measuring, audit and review<br /><br />

				Unit IFC1: Fire Safety and Risk Management<br /><br />
				
				Managing Fire Safety<br />
				Principles of Fire and Explosion<br />
				Causes and Prevention of Fires<br />
				Fire Protection in Buildings<br />
				Safety of People in the Event of a Fire<br />
				Fire Safety Risk Assessment<br /><br />
				
				

				Unit IFC2: Workplace-Based Practical Assessment (Fire Risk Assessment)<br /><br />
				


<b>Method of Study:&nbsp;</b><a href="http://www.nistelearning.com/" target="_blank">E-learning </a>(Online) <br />
<br /></p>


			</li>
			<li>
				<h3>Assessment Method</h3>

				<p>NEBOSH International Fire certification assessment consists of two examinations (Unit I &amp; Unit II) &amp; a practical Fire risk assessment. </p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<h3>E-learning (Online)</h3>
				<span><img src="images/plus.png" alt="plus" height="20"></span>
				<p>Complete Course - 120 study hours <br />	
					Unit IGC1 - 60 study hours<br />
					Unit IFC1/2 - 60 study hours</p>
			</li>	
			<li>
				<h3>Exemption</h3>
				<span><img src="images/plus.png" alt="plus" height="20"></span>
				<p>
				International General Certificate (IGC1) is the core unit for all of the NEBOSH International Health and Safety Certificates, so to advance a NEBOSH Certificate you need to study IGC1 along with the applicable specialist unit and practical assessment. <br /><br />	
				If you have been awarded a <a href="http://www.nebosh.org.uk/Qualifications/Awards/default.asp?cref=633&ct=2" target="_blank">NEBOSH International Certification </a>the last 5 years and wish to take another, you will be exempt from IGC1 and can simply add the specialist unit (IFC1) and practical assessment (IFC2) to achieve the new award. <br /><br />

			</li>	
